  "overall_strengths": [
    "Good APK-first ergonomics: accepts an APK or pulls one from a device, then produces both machine-readable-ish text and analyst-friendly XMind output",
    "Strong at surface enumeration: exported components, intent-filters, secret codes, permissions, file inventory, framework fingerprinting, and network security config extraction",
    "Useful for Android-specific hardening checks where simple syntactic evidence is meaningful, such as `debuggable`, exported `ContentProvider` heuristics, `SslErrorHandler.proceed`, or `FLAG_SECURE` absence",
    "Evidence is usually concrete and verifiable: class names, component names, Smali file paths, XML-derived domain settings"
  ],
  "overall_limitations": [
    "No taint analysis, no source-sink reasoning, no inter-procedural flow tracking",
    "Smali analysis is almost entirely regex-based and often only checks file presence, not reachability or exploitability",
    "Current checkout defect: `getFileContent()` reads only the first line of a file, which likely breaks or severely weakens all detectors that rely on later instruction scanning and register backtracking",
    "`checkForExistenceInFolder()` builds the `--exclude-dir` argument incorrectly, so configured folder exclusions are effectively not trustworthy",
    "`findPropertyEnabledWebViews()` assumes file access is enabled when `setAllowFileAccess(...)` is absent, which is a built-in false-positive bias",
    "`checkOKHttpCertificatePinning()` has a semantic mismatch: it appends a location when `CertificatePinner.Builder.add(...)` is found but `certificatePinner(...)` is not found in the same file, yet XMind later interprets that list as evidence of pinning usage",
    "Output granularity is usually class/file level, not method/instruction level, which limits downstream precision",
    "The tool reports both \"bad evidence\" and \"good hardening present\" in the same channel, so consumers must model signal polarity explicitly",
    "Taint relevance: Low",
    "The tool is helpful as a prior over attack surfaces and security-sensitive APIs, but it does not explain whether untrusted data reaches those APIs",
    "The only \"dataflow-like\" logic is shallow same-file constant backtracking for booleans and cipher modes; that is not taint analysis"
  ],
